{ My second OTB game ever and second of this day. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 (5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5 { I dislike these types of positions on principle. } 8... Be6 9. Nbd2 Nc5 10. c3 d4 11. Ng5 Qxg5 (11... Bd5 { [%cal Gf3g5] } 12. Nxf7 { [%csl Gc6][%cal Gd5f7,Gb3f7,Ge8f7,Gd1f3,Gf3c6] } 12... Kxf7 13. Qf3+ Ke6) 12. Qf3 O-O-O 13. Bxe6+ fxe6 14. Qxc6) 5... b5 6. Bb3 Be7 7. c3 { [%cal Gd3d4] } 7... d6 8. Nbd2 { [%cal Gd2f1,Gf1g3] } 8... Bg4?! { My idea with Nbd2 before castling was designed around stopping Bg4 from annoying me. } { [%cal Gd2f1,Gf1g3] } 9. h3 Bh5 { [%cal Gd2f1,Gf1g3] } 10. a4 O-O 11. Nf1 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 Na5 13. Bc2 c5 { This was the idea behind Bxf3. By getting in c5, black hopes that his queenside space compensates for the lack of the bishop pair. Personally, I was more worried about 13... d5, opening up the position while my king was in the center. Ultimately, the computer likes my position in all of these lines because my attack is almost unstoppable. } (13... d5 14. Ne3 d4 15. Nf5 { My idea. }) 14. Ne3 c4 15. dxc4?! (15. d4?! exd4 16. cxd4 Nc6 17. Nf5 g6 { everything works out for white here, but only barely }) 15... Nxc4?! (15... bxc4 { This was the more annoying situation to me. Now, my backward b pawn becomes a targetable weakness unless my bishop permanently remains on c1. } { [%cal Ge1g1] } 16. O-O Rb8 17. Nf5 Nb3) 16. O-O Qc7 (16... Nxe3 17. Bxe3 { [%csl Gc2,Ge3] } 17... d5 18. Rfd1 $14) 17. Nf5 Rfd8 18. Rd1 Rab8?! { This move is too slow. Now I have time to push black back on the queenside before initiating my kingside play. } 19. axb5 axb5 (19... Rxb5 20. b3 Nb6 21. Rxa6) 20. b3 Nb6 (20... Na5 21. Nxe7+ Qxe7 (21... Kf8 22. Nf5) 22. Rxa5 $18) 21. Bg5 { I couldn't see any immediate sacrifices that won, but I was getting very excited about all the different possibilities. } 21... h6?! { But this is just too much. I wanted to place the knight or bishop on h6 even without there being a pawn there. Now I saw until move 27 and felt that this must be enough for me to win. } (21... Re8 22. Ra6 Nbd7 { At the least I can cash in on the backward d pawn. } 23. Nxe7+ Rxe7 24. Raxd6 $16) (21... Ra8 22. Bd3 Rxa1 23. Rxa1 Qxc3?? 24. Nxe7+ Kf8 25. Rc1 $18) 22. Nxh6+ (22. Bxh6 gxh6 23. Qg3+ Kf8 24. Qg7+ Ke8 25. Bd3! Nc8 26. Nxh6 { [%csl Gf7] }) 22... gxh6 23. Bxf6 Bxf6 24. Qxf6 Qxc3 25. Ra7 { [%cal Gd8d7,Gb6d7] } (25. Rac1 Qc8 26. Rxd6 { The more controlled way to play. I got too excited with Ra7. }) 25... Rd7 (25... Nd7 26. Qxd6 Qxc2 27. Rxd7 Rxd7 28. Qxd7 { Transposes to the game. }) 26. Rxd7? (26. Rd3!! { Missed in the game. } 26... Qxc2 27. Rg3+ Kf8 (27... Kh7 28. Qg7#) 28. Qh8+ Ke7 29. Qxb8 Rxa7 30. Qxa7+ $18) 26... Nxd7 27. Qxd6 Qxc2 28. Qxd7 Qxe4 { But when I found myself here, I was amazed that black was still holding on. Thankfully, I found this crazy idea (Rd3) to get my rook into the attack at the expense of a pawn, and it's completely winning. Both of us were getting lower on time here, but I was down to 5 minutes. } 29. Rd3! { [%csl Ge1] } 29... Qe1+ 30. Kh2 Qxf2 31. Rg3+ Kh7 (31... Kh8 32. Qd6 $18 { [%csl Gf8,Gb8,Gh6,Ge5] } 32... Qb6 { seemed to be the only try to defend, but: } 33. Qxe5+ f6 34. Qf4 Kh7 35. Qg4 $18) (31... Kf8 32. Qd6+ $18 { [%csl Gb8] }) 32. Rf3 { and f7 is undefensible } { [%csl Gf7] } 32... Qc2 (32... Qe2 33. Rxf7+ Kg6 (33... Kh8 34. Rh7+ Kg8 35. Qf7#) 34. Qf5#) 33. Qxf7+ (33. Rxf7+ Kh8 { and I couldn't see the finish: although there is one: } 34. Qd6! $18 { [%cal Gd6h6,Gd6f6] }) 33... Kh8 34. Qf6+ Kh7 35. Qe7+ Kh8 36. Qxe5+ Kg8 37. Qxb8+ Kg7 38. Qf8+ Kg6 39. Qg8+ Kh5 40. Qg4# { My young opponent played it out to mate, but my low time didn't effect much as there was not much left to calculate. } 1-0


