{ My third OTB game ever and third of the day. We have caught up with the 3 round tournament, so this was my first proper classical OTB game.

At this point I was exhausted, had not had a break for food, and was worried going into the game that something bad would happen. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nge7 4. O-O g6 5. c3 Bg7 6. d4 exd4 7. cxd4 d5 8. exd5 Nxd5 9. Re1+ Be6 10. Ng5?! (10. Bg5 Qd6 11. Nbd2 O-O 12. Ne4 Qb4 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. Qc1 $14) 10... Qd6 (10... O-O!? 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Nxe6 fxe6 { I wasn't sure how to evaluate this position. Black's pawn structure is a mess, but I've traded off all my developed pieces in order to do it. I need a knight on f3, otherwise I'm getting mated, but that drops the d4 pawn. } 13. Nd2 (13. Rxe6? c5 14. dxc5 Nf4 15. Re1 Nd3 $15) 13... Bxd4 14. Nf3 Bg7 $13 { I was also worried about Rxf3 possibilities if I get too greedy. }) 11. Nxe6 fxe6 12. Nc3 Nxc3?? 13. bxc3 O-O { It seemed to me that we were in a Grunfeld-like structure except black didn't have any counterplay against my center with a c5 pawn break. And in fact the computer agrees that this is terrible for black. } 14. Qb3 Rfe8 15. Ba3 Qd7 16. Bc4 Nd8 (16... Na5 17. Rxe6 Nxb3 18. Rxe8# { A pretty mate I saw. }) 17. Re3 Kh8 18. Rae1 { I felt in complete control of the position. But taking that "free" pawn meant giving up my beastly light-squared bishop. I was afraid to cash-in because the resulting endgame might be drawn. } 18... c6 19. g3 { How long can I hold my ground? } 19... b5 20. Bxe6?! { Not long at all. } (20. Bf1!? Qd5? { This was the move that I thought held everything together for black. But actually I can just trade here because the c pawn must protect the b pawn! } (20... a5 21. Bg2 a4 22. Qd1 Kg8 { If I wasn't starving, I would have loved to play this position further... }) 21. Qxd5! (21. Bg2 Qxb3 22. axb3 { I saw this position in the game and was not convinced. } { [%cal Gh8g8,Gg8f7] }) 21... cxd5 22. Bxb5 $16) 20... Nxe6 21. Rxe6 Rxe6 22. Qxe6 Qxe6 23. Rxe6 Rc8 24. Bc5 a5 25. a3 a4 26. f4 { I had seen this position from before I cashed in on e6. But I couldn't see anything better. Even when I ended up here, I was unable to find any way forward. } 26... Kg8 $10 { After 9 straight hours of chess, and no break for food, I was exhausted. I agreed to a draw just so I could eat. I was more afraid that I would bungle the game completely than I was concerned with winning. } 27. Kf2 (27. g4 Bf8 28. Bxf8 Rxf8 { and I thought during the game that this was drawn as well, but actually after Re4, I can still fight on for a win. }) 27... Kf7 28. Re7+ Kg8 (28... Kf6?? 29. g4 Bf8 30. g5+ Kf5 31. Rf7+ Ke6 32. Rxf8 $18) 29. Kf3 { I thought in the game that Kf3 would only lead to a draw, but in fact... } 29... Bf8 30. Re5! Bxc5 (30... Bg7 31. Re6 Bf8 (31... Kf7 32. Re7+ Kg8 { A worse position than in the game. }) 32. g4 Bxc5 33. dxc5 Kf7 34. Rd6 h5 35. g5 Rc7 36. h4 Rc8 37. f5 gxf5 38. Kf4 Kg7 39. Kxf5 Rf8+ 40. Rf6 Rc8 $18) 31. Rxc5 Kf7 { I thought this was a draw with no way for white to make progress - completely missing d5. Rather than trade even more pieces, I instead accepted my opponent's draw offer on move 26. } 32. d5 $18 (32. Ke4 Ke6 (32... Ke7 33. g4 Kd6 34. h4 Re8+ 35. Re5 Rf8 36. g5 (36. f5 gxf5+ 37. gxf5 $16)) 33. Rxc6+! Rxc6 34. d5+ $18) 1/2-1/2


