1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 d5 { The end of my knowledge on this line. I know that stopping e4 is crucial. } (4... c5!?) 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 O-O (6... c5 7. cxd5 exd5 8. e3 c4 { If I had this position again, I would go with this. It clarifies the pawn structure, stops his light squared bishop getting on the most active diagonal, and gives me a more tangible plan I can shoot for: convert the queenside majority into a passed pawn. 2021: With 2 years experience and a 100% winrate in these positions, I've still determined that they're too scary for black and instead play 4...c5 }) 7. cxd5 exd5 8. e3 c5 9. Bd3 { His bishop reaches a good diagonal, and I am unsure how best to proceed except to try and stop e4 from hitting. } 9... Re8 10. Ne2 Nc6 11. O-O g6?! { Here, I thought for a long time to come up with g6. I was envisioning some sort of kingside attack with the possibility of an open h file and rook move to the open file. It's more dream than reality, as my opponent's direct play showcases. } 12. Ng3 Qe7 { Designed to stop e4, but it doesn't even work. } 13. Ra2!? { The inactive rook swings over to the e file to help out in the e4 break. } { [%cal Ga1a2] } (13. e4 cxd4 14. cxd4 $16) 13... h5 14. Re2 c4?! { I have to play c4 before I can destabilize the knight with h4. But strategically, this move is just bad. There's no way to get my queenside pawns breaking through before white pushes through in the center. } (14... h4 15. e4?! hxg3 16. exd5 gxh2+ 17. Kh1 Qd6 18. dxc6 Rxe2 19. Qxe2 { I thought this would be bad for black, but ultimately it's completely ok. }) 15. Bb1 h4 16. Nh1 { My kingside play looks strong right now, but it's all an illusion. The breakthrough is too slow.. } 16... Kg7 (16... Nh5 17. Nf2 f5) 17. Nf2 Nh5 18. e4 { I wanted to play Ng3 so badly, but I saw to conclusion a line in which it fails. The position is already lost, as I've been playing on the wrong side of the board the entire game. } { [%cal Gh5g3] } 18... f5 (18... Ng3 19. hxg3 hxg3 20. Nh1 Qh4 21. Nxg3 Qxg3 22. exd5 Rh8 (22... Rxe2 23. Qxe2) 23. dxc6 $18) 19. Rfe1 fxe4 20. Nxe4! { Straight up wins an exchange without any of the danger of fxe4. } (20. fxe4 Ng3 21. hxg3 hxg3 22. Nh3 { I was hoping to make it messy rather than go down without a fight. } 22... Bg4 (22... Qh4 23. exd5 { [%cal Gc8h3] } 23... Rh8 24. dxc6 Bxh3 25. Re7+ $18) 23. exd5 $18) 20... dxe4 21. Rxe4 (21. Bxe4 Qf7 22. Bxg6 Qxg6 23. Rxe8 Bh3 24. R8e2 { This looked scary, but I could see that my opponent was fine here too. }) 21... Qf7 22. Rxe8 Nf6 23. R8e2 (23. R8e4 { The move I would have played. I could tell that even in this line, I'm completely busted. } 23... Nxe4 24. fxe4) 23... Bd7 24. Bg5 Nd5 25. Qd2 (25. Be4 Nxc3 26. Bxc6 Nxd1 27. Bxd7 Qxd7 28. Re7+ Qxe7 29. Rxe7+ Kf8 { Even here I'm losing. }) 25... Re8 (25... Rh8 26. Be4 $18) 26. Rxe8 Bxe8 27. Bxh4 { White is clearly converting this one, so I resigned. } 1-0


