1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. b3 Bg7 4. Bb2 O-O 5. g3 d6 6. d4 { I have no experience in English-like structures. So I tried to stay flexible, but simultaneously offer to go into a Benoni if white so chooses. } 6... c5 7. dxc5? (7. Bg2 Qa5+ 8. Nc3 Ne4!?) (7. d5 e6 { [%cal Ge2e4] }) 7... dxc5 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. Bg2 Nc6 10. O-O Bf5 { I felt that given one or two moves, I should actually have the advantage because my rook is already on the open file, and my knights are well centralized. } { [%csl Gb1][%cal Gf3h4,Gf5e4] } 11. Na3 (11. Nbd2!?) 11... a6 { [%cal Ga3c2,Gf5e4] } (11... Be4 12. Nb5 a6 13. Nc3 { I can't immediately offset white's bishop because the knight will reroute itself to c3 if I don't first play a6. } { [%csl Ge4,Gg2] }) 12. Nh4 Be4 { The move you want to play. If you can offset white's king's indian bishop, then black is starting to be better. } (12... Rd2! 13. Bc3 Rxe2 14. Bf3 Re6 $17 { Black can snag the pawn and escape with the rook. }) 13. f3!? (13. Bxf6?? Bxg2 14. Bxe7 Bxf1 15. Bxd8 Bxa1 $19) 13... Bf5 { If I'm fine with the pawn structure that arises after Nxf5 here, I should instead be considering allowing Nxf5 before allowing white to take the center! } (13... g5!! { This move didn't even cross my mind. And yet, it solves every single problem black has! } 14. fxe4 gxh4 15. gxh4 (15. Rfd1 hxg3 16. hxg3 { Black is left with a better pawn structure. }) 15... Rd2 $17 { [%csl Ge4,Ge2][%cal Gc6d4] }) 14. e4 Bd7 15. e5 Ne8 16. f4 { [%cal Ge8c7,Gc7e6,Ge6d4] } 16... Nd6!? { [%csl Gb2,Ga1,Ga3] } (16... Nc7 17. Nc2 Ne6 18. Rad1 { I saw this position from far away and realized that I can never really land a knight on d4. Still, the computer prefers this line with a5-a4 ideas to soften up the queenside. }) 17. Nc2 (17. exd6?? Bxb2 18. dxe7 Re8 19. Rad1 Bg4! { I saw the knight could not be taken. }) 17... Nf5 { [%cal Gf5d4,Gc6d4] } 18. Nxf5! { I completely underestimated this move. I figured that I could put my bishop on a good diagonal again, I would be fine, but in fact the other knight is coming to make my bishop's life hard once again. } 18... Bxf5 19. Bxc6?! { No need to give up the bishop pair to ruin the pawn structure. The pressure along the diagonal is more important than the pawn structure. } (19. Ne3 $16) 19... bxc6 20. Ne3 { [%csl Gg7,Ge6][%cal Gf5e6] } 20... a5 (20... Bh3!? 21. Rf3 { I was scared about this move - with g4 coming to trap my bishop, but the computer finds a way to make this look silly. } { [%cal Gg3g4] } 21... Rd2 22. Bc3 Rd3 23. Rc1 Bg4! 24. Nxg4 Rxf3 25. Kg2 Rd3 $17) 21. Nxf5 gxf5 22. Ba3 a4 (22... e6 23. Bxc5 Bf8 24. Bxf8 Kxf8 { A better try. I didn't need that queenside pawn anyway, and white doesn't have any passed pawns in this position. Black has better drawing chances in this rook and pawn endgame. } 25. Rfd1 c5 { [%cal Gd8d4] } 26. Kg2) 23. Bxc5 axb3 24. axb3 (24. Bxe7?? Rd7 25. Bc5 Rxa2 $17) 24... Rab8 25. Bxe7 Re8 26. Bd6 Rxb3 { I'm in full-on trade all the pawns away mode. But there's too many. } 27. Ra6 f6! { Always play f6. More trades, more! } 28. Re1 (28. Rxc6 fxe5 29. fxe5 Bxe5 30. Re1?? { I was still seeing ways white could blunder this away. } 30... Bd4+ 31. Kf1 { [%cal Ge8e1] } 31... Rf3+ 32. Kg2 Rf2+ 33. Kh3 Rxe1 $19) 28... fxe5 29. Bxe5 Rd8 { [%csl Gd2,Gb2] } 30. Bxg7 Kxg7 31. Rxc6 Rb2! { The sneaky threat is Rdd2 - with unavoidable perpetuals. Unfortunately, white found the only move to avoid all perpetuals, and instantly end the game. } 32. Ra1! { [%cal Gd8d2] } (32. c5 Rdd2 $10) 32... Kf8 { [%cal Gd8d2,Ga1a8,Gf8e7,Ga8a7,Ge7d8,Gc6c8] } (32... Rdd2?? 33. Ra7+ Kf8 34. Rc8+ Rd8 35. Rxd8#) 33. Rc7 $18 { Black has no more threats of perpetual, and I could see the simple plan of pushing the c pawn to c6, playing Rd7 to trade rooks, and keep on pushing. So I resigned rather than play down what will soon be 3 pawns. } { [%cal Gc4c5,Gc5c6,Gc7d7,Gc6c7,Gc7c8] } (33. h3 Rdd2 34. Rc8+ Ke7 35. Ra7+ Kd6 36. Rd8+ Kc5 37. Rxd2 Rxd2 { Even here, white could avoid the perpetual. }) 1-0


