1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O { [%cal Gf8c5,Gf8e7,Gb7b5] } 5... d6 { A passive line for black in the Ruy Lopez. } { [%cal Gc2c3,Ga4c2] } 6. c3 { [%cal Gd2d4] } 6... Be7 7. Re1 b5 8. Bc2 (8. Bb3 { This move would transition to the mainline Ruy. But because I was able to get in c3 before b5 hit, I have a new retreat square that I deemed had to be better for white than in the mainline. I thought that after any Nb4 moves, I could "retreat" to b3, a great square for my bishop. } 8... O-O 9. h3 Na5 10. Bc2 c5) 8... O-O 9. h3 Be6 { Bad, but for a complicated reason. Here I realized that my opponent is stopping my Bb3 ideas in response to Nb4, and indeed he is. However, white has another interesting try that I didn't fully appreciate. } { [%cal Gd2d4,Gd4d5,Gc2b3] } (9... Bb7 10. d4 exd4 11. cxd4 Nb4 12. Bb3 { [%cal Gb3g8,Gc2e4] }) 10. d4 exd4 11. cxd4 Nb4 { [%cal Gb1c3] } 12. Nbd2 (12. d5! { The only try for an advantage. } 12... Nxc2 13. Qxc2 Bd7 { I saw how quickly c6 was coming, and figured white's center couldn't be maintained, but completely missed: } 14. Nd4! $16) (12. Nc3? Nxc2 13. Qxc2 b4 14. Ne2 d5 15. e5 Ne4 $10) 12... Nxc2 13. Qxc2 Rc8 { [%cal Gc7c5,Gd4d5] } 14. b3 (14. Nf1? d5 15. e5 Ne4 $10 { [%cal Gd2f1,Gf1g3] }) (14. d5 Bd7 15. Nd4 { A worse version of the previous line, but still probably best. }) 14... c6!? (14... c5 15. d5 Bd7 { I fully expected this line, where black's queenside expansion is scary, but white isn't missing the light squared bishop so much. }) 15. Bb2 { [%cal Gd2f1,Gf1g3] } 15... Qd7 16. Ng5 (16. Rad1 Bxh3 17. gxh3 Qxh3 18. Qc3 Qg4+ 19. Kh1 { I knew this wasn't working, but why deal with an attack when you don't need to. }) 16... h6 (16... d5 17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. e5 Nh5 $15 { [%cal Gh5f4,Gc6c5] }) 17. Nxe6 fxe6 { A much scarier recapture for white. } 18. Nf3 { [%cal Gc6c5,Gd6d5,Ge6e5] } 18... Nh5! { Here I had my longest thinking of the game, as I began to take in all the attacking ideas black had against my king. I'm proud to say that I successfully calculated the game line correctly. } { [%cal Gh5f4,Gf4h3,Gg2h3,Gf8f3] } 19. Re3 Nf4 { [%cal Gg1h2] } 20. Qd2 (20. Rd1 { The move you want to play fails } 20... Qe8 21. Kh2 Qg6 22. g3 { [%cal Gf4d5,Gg6c2] } 22... Nd5! $17) 20... Qe8 21. Kh2 Qg6 (21... Qh5! { Suddenly I saw this line and realized that black has too much pressure on f3 and h3 for white to avoid compromising something. }) 22. g3 Nh5 { [%cal Ge7g5] } 23. Rd1 (23. Rc1 Rf7 24. Qe2 Rcf8 { I didn't want to line up my pieces on the dark squares, once you see the knight can no longer capture the bishop. } { [%cal Ge7g5,Gf3g5,Gf7f2] }) 23... Rf7 24. Qe2 Rcf8 { [%csl Gh5,Gg6,Gf7,Gf8,Ge7] } 25. d5? { Rather than sit idly by and defend any longer, I wanted some activity for my pieces. Unfortunately I completely missed the following exchange. } (25. Ba3 Bg5 26. Red3 $10) 25... cxd5 26. exd5 e5! { I missed this move entirely. Now I had to completely reassess the situation again. e4 is the immediate threat, so white has to play precisely to hold on. } { [%csl Ge3][%cal Ge5e4,Ge3f3,Ge2f3] } (26... exd5??) 27. Rdd3 (27. Rc1?? e4 $19 { [%cal Gf7f2] }) 27... Rxf3?? { Instead of building up the pressure further, my opponent suddenly takes my knight. At first I panicked, thinking I had overlooked something, but no, this is simply just an exchange. } (27... e4?? 28. Rxe4 { White barely holds on. }) (27... Bg5 28. Re4 { Here I thought I had everything under control too. }) (27... Bh4!! { Black wins with a spectacular shot. The g3 pawn is attacked too many times and it's overworked - defending both h4 and f4. } 28. Qe1 Bd8!! { This maneuver would not have been easy for my opponent to see. } { [%cal Gd8b6] }) 28. Rxf3 Rxf3 29. Rxf3 (29. Qxf3?? e4 $19 { Maybe my opponent thought Qxf3 was forced? }) 29... e4 30. Rc3 Bf6 31. Rc8+ Kh7 32. Bxf6 (32. Qg4! { I wanted to play this move so badly to trade queens, but I realized that I shouldn't be so keen to trade off the queens until I actually win a pawn somewhere. } 32... Qxg4 33. hxg4 Bxb2 34. gxh5 $18 { But in actual fact, this is simply game over - the a6 pawn is done for, and now I don't have to worry anymore about perpetual checks as in the game. }) 32... Nxf6 33. Ra8 Qf5 34. Rxa6 Qxd5 35. Ra5? (35. Rb6 { More active - and ensures the line that occurred in the game doesn't work. } 35... Qd3?? 36. Qxd3 exd3 37. Rxd6 $18) 35... Qd3! 36. Qb2? (36. Qe1 { The only try to save the game. }) 36... Qf1?? (36... Nd7! 37. Ra7 Ne5! $10 { I thought my mate threats would be sufficient to ensure the knight could never get active. But amazingly the knight on e5 simply dominates the board. } { [%cal Ge5f3] }) 37. Ra7 { [%cal Ga7g7,Gb2f6,Gf6g7] } 37... Kg6 38. a4 bxa4 39. bxa4 { Finally I have a passed pawn, so now it's time to push it baby. } 39... d5 40. Rc7 Qa6 41. Qb5 Qd6 42. Qb7 { [%cal Gc7g7] } 42... Qf8 43. Qb6 { [%cal Gb6g6] } (43. a5?? Ng4+! $10) 43... Qa8 44. a5 d4 { A good try, but I calculated why it didn't work. } 45. a6 Kh7? { Instead, my opponent immediately blunders away the game by walking back into a pin. Regardless, it was only a matter of time at this point. } (45... e3 46. fxe3 dxe3 47. a7 e2 48. Qb1+ Kg5 { [%cal Gc7g7] } (48... Kh5 $18 { [%cal Gc7g7] }) 49. Rxg7+ $18) (45... d3 46. a7 d2 47. Rd7 e3 48. fxe3 $18) 46. Qxf6 $18 1-0


