1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 { [%cal Gg1f3] } 3. Nc3 Bb4 { [%cal Gf2f3,Ge2e4] } 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5 { [%cal Gd8a5,Ga5c3,Ga5c5] } 6. Nf3 (6. Bg5 Qa5 $15) (6. f3!? d5 7. cxd5 exd5 8. e3 c4 { [%cal Gf1d3,Gb1h7] }) 6... Nc6 7. e3 O-O 8. Bd3 d6 (8... d5!? { I was also considering this move against all odds. While it forceably undoubles white's pawns, I was visualizing a certain position in the f3 Nimzo, where white is now worse than in that line. } 9. cxd5 exd5 10. O-O c4 11. Bc2 $15 { [%cal Gb7b5,Ga7a5,Gb5b4] }) 9. O-O (9. e4 { The move I was most scared of. I was mentally committed to playing e5 in response to e4. }) 9... b6 { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gc6a5,Ga5c4,Gc8a6,Ga6c4] } 10. Qd2? { A clear mistake. The queen belongs on e2, defending the c4 weakness, supporting an e4 push, and getting out of the way of the bishop. } 10... Ba6 11. Qe2 Qc7?! { I was trying to stay flexible here (possibly going for a Na5 cxd4 follow-up to further attack the c pawn), but white's direct play is too fast. } { [%cal Gc5d4,Gc3d4] } 12. d5 (12. e4 e5 13. d5 Na5 { And my queen is clearly misplaced on c7. }) 12... Na5 13. e4 Nb3 (13... exd5 { [%cal Gf8e8] } 14. cxd5 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 c4!! { I didn't even consider this line. Here I change the position completely, but I will soon have two incredible knights on c5 and b3, and white's bishop just became bad. } { [%cal Gf6d7,Gd7c5,Ga5b3] }) 14. Rb1 Nxc1 (14... exd5! { It's apparently still not too late to transition to the other line. }) 15. Rbxc1 e5 { I had taken almost an hour to reach this position, but now I became free to move much faster. I've nearly achieved a good knight vs bad bishop position, where the only break white has in the position (f4) permanently gives me the e5 square. If I could trade my bishop for his knight and plant a knight on f4 or e5, I'm strategically won. } 16. h3 Bc8 (16... Rae8 { In retrospect, I would have preferred to connect rooks before retreating the bishop. }) 17. Nh2 Qe7 18. Kh1 (18. f4? exf4 19. Rxf4 Nd7 $17) 18... Bd7 { [%cal Ga8e8] } 19. Rg1 { Here I realized my opponent was going for a g4 push, not an f4 push. But this permanently rests control of the f4 square. If only my knight could hop there once g4 is played... } { [%csl Gf4][%cal Gg2g4,Gf6g8,Gg8e7,Ge7g6,Gg6f4] } 19... Kh8 20. g4 g5? { Unnecessary. I figured if white's knight would hop into f5, I could always take it with my bishop - whereas the same cannot be said about the f4 square. But there's no need to give my opponent any squares whatsoever. } { [%csl Gh5,Gf5] } 21. Nf1 Ng8 22. Ng3 Qf6 { [%cal Gg8e7,Ge7g6,Gg6f4] } 23. Kg2 Ne7 24. Nh5 { [%cal Gd7f5] } 24... Qh6 25. Rh1 { [%cal Gh3h4] } 25... Ng6 { [%cal Gh6h5,Gg6f4] } 26. Qe3 { Aiming for the h4 break because the g pawn is now pinned. } { [%cal Gh3h4] } 26... Nh4+ 27. Kf1 { I was down to 20 minutes at this point, and calculated the following line before realizing that I don't have any winning chances there. So rather than offer a draw, I decided I might as well see what would happen with my last remaining try. } 27... f5! (27... f6 28. Qe2 Be8 29. Ng3 Bg6 { I was initially considering this line - to enter a good knight vs bad bishop endgame. But let's be honest - my knight isn't the best knight in the word, and even if it actually reaches f4, it's not hitting anything crucial in combination with any of my other pieces. }) 28. exf5 Bxf5 { [%cal Gg4f5,Gh6h5] } 29. Bxf5 Nxf5 30. gxf5 Qxh5 31. Qe4 { [%cal Gh5f7,Gf7f5] } 31... Qf7? (31... Rf6! { The move I had initially considered. Black refuses to trade queens, even at the expense of not winning a pawn. } 32. Qg4 Qf7 33. Qxg5 Rxf5 { [%csl Gc1,Gh1][%cal Ga8f8] } 34. Qd2 Rf8 35. Rh2 { I didn't see any immediate breakthrough here and was running lower and lower on time, but in retrospect of course this has to be better than winning a pawn and trading everything away. } { [%cal Gf5f3,Ge5e4,Ge4e3] }) 32. h4 Qxf5 33. Qxf5 Rxf5 34. hxg5 Rxg5 35. Rh6 { A good try. But it immediately fails for one specific reason I didn't see in the game. } 35... Rg6?! (35... Rag8! { [%cal Gg5g1] } 36. Ke2 R8g6 37. Rxg6 Rxg6 { Now black keeps his passed h pawn and any hope of winning alive. } { [%cal Gh7h1] }) 36. Rxg6 hxg6 37. a4 Kg7 38. a5 Rh8 { [%csl Ga7][%cal Gb6a5] } (38... bxa5!? 39. Ra1 { [%cal Ga8f8,Ga1a5,Gf8f4,Ga5a7,Gg7f6,Gf4c4] } 39... Kf6 (39... a4! 40. Rxa4 a5 $19 { [%csl Ge5,Gg6,Gf2] }) 40. Rxa5 a6! { Black is incredibly passive, but the computer suggests this is enough to win. I assessed this as completely even, as his rook completely dominates mine, and I have no passed pawns. But essentially, this turns into a king and pawn endgame with an e and g pawn against an f pawn - a theoretical win. }) 39. Ke2 { [%cal Gb6a5,Gh8a8,Ga7a6] } 39... Rh4 $10 { Draw offered and accepted. Amazingly, black still had winning chances until this final move. } { [%cal Ga5b6,Ga7b6,Gc1b1,Ge2d3] } (39... bxa5 40. Ra1 Ra8 41. Rxa5 a6 { Black must transpose to the previous line if he wanted to win. }) 1/2-1/2


