{ I was filled with determination to crush my opponent after failing to convert two good positions in a row. This game I decided that I would play actively, even if I couldn't calculate if it would work out for me. }
1. e4 c6 (1... e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 { [%csl Gc8] }) 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Ne4 5. d4 { I've never seen this move before, so now I'm making it up as I go. } (5. Nxe4 { I know this is a mistake. } 5... dxe4 6. Ng5 Qd5 $10 { [%cal Gd5e5] }) (5. Ne2 { [%cal Gd2d3] } 5... Qb6 { [%cal Gb6f2] } 6. d4 { I know this is theory. } { Vachier Lagrave, Maxime - Anand, V., 0-1, 4th Sinquefield Cup 2016, https://lichess.org/BAoU9yua }) 5... Bg4 6. Be2?! { [%csl Ge2] } (6. Bd3! { If black is forced into taking the knight, then white's light squared bishop stands best on d3, as in typical French winawer pawn structures. } 6... Nxc3 7. bxc3) (6. Nxe4! dxe4 7. h3 Bh5 8. g4 exf3 9. gxh5 $16 { [%cal Gd1f3,Gd8d4] }) 6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 e6 { [%cal Gc6c5] } 8. h3 Bh5 9. O-O c5 { [%csl Gd4,Gc6,Gb6] } (9... Be7 { I was certain black should be getting on with normal development, but I could sense my opponent wasn't quite sure what they were doing, so I figured they would be unable to punish me if I went for a little bit more than equality - by striking for a French Winawer, but with the light squared bishop outside the pawn chain. }) 10. Rb1 { [%csl Gh5,Gc8] } 10... Qc7 11. Nh2? { A positional mistake. White is trading their good bishop for black's bad bishop as well as removing lots of threats against my shaky king by trading pieces. } (11. c4! { The move I was most scared of. } { [%cal Gc4d5] } 11... dxc4 (11... Nc6 12. cxd5 exd5 13. dxc5 $16) 12. d5! $16 { These are only the type of moves you play if you've been on the receiving side of some terrifying Caro Kann, advanced variation attacks. }) 11... Bxe2 12. Qxe2 Nc6 13. Be3 { [%csl Gc5,Gc3,Gc2][%cal Gc5c4,Gd4c5] } 13... b6 { [%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5,Gd4c5,Gb6c5] } 14. f4 { [%cal Gf4f5,Ge6f5,Gf1f5] } 14... g6 { [%cal Gf4f5,Gg6f5] } (14... cxd4! 15. cxd4 Ne7 { [%cal Ge7f5] } 16. g4 Qc4 17. Qf2 g6 { Somewhat unclear, but black should have sufficient counterplay on the c file to have a slight edge. }) 15. Ng4 { [%cal Gg4f6,Gg4h6] } (15. g4!? Be7 16. f5 gxf5 17. gxf5 Rg8+ 18. Kh1) 15... Be7 16. Nh6 (16. Nf6+!? Bxf6 17. exf6 cxd4!? 18. cxd4 Na5 { [%csl Ge2,Ge8] }) 16... Rc8 { Macho chess, but still tempting fate. I'm basically saying to white "show me a forced checkmate," otherwise black is positionally won. } { [%cal Gc6d4] } 17. g4? { A mistake but an understandable one. My opponent underestimated my continuation. } (17. Nxf7!? Kxf7 18. f5 { [%csl Gh5] } 18... exf5 19. Rxf5+!? gxf5 20. e6+! Ke8 21. Qh5+ Kd8 { Black can escape the onslaught. } { [%csl Gg5][%cal Gh5g5,Gc7e7] }) (17. f5! gxf5 18. Nxf7! { This type of attack from white must have been attempted. I was calculating some of these lines before playing Rc8, but didn't see a clear loss for black anywhere. } { [%cal Ge2h5] }) (17. dxc5! bxc5 18. Rb5 Na5 19. Rfb1 $14 { [%cal Ga5c4,Gb5b7] }) 17... cxd4! { [%csl Gc3,Gc2][%cal Ge3d4,Gc6a5,Ga5c4] } 18. cxd4 (18. f5!? dxe3 19. fxe6 fxe6 { It's not quite enough. }) 18... Bf8!! 19. g5?? { My opponent completely crumbles under the pressure. Now black is complete control of the f5 square, and has nothing more to fear. } (19. f5!? { Like it or not, white has to go all-in with this attack. If it doesn't work, at least he died trying. } { [%cal Ge3h6] } 19... Bxh6 20. Bxh6 gxf5 21. gxf5 (21. c3! Ne7 { [%cal Gb1c1] } 22. Rbc1 Rg8 $17) 21... Rg8+ 22. Kh1 Nxd4 { [%cal Gc7c2,Gd4c2] } 23. Qf2 Nxf5 { Here black holds fine. But white can play with more gusto. }) 19... Bxh6 20. gxh6 Ne7! { [%cal Ge7f5] } (20... Na5!? 21. Qg4 Qc3 22. Rbe1 { Did I really want to further tempt fate with the queen getting to f6? }) 21. Rbc1 (21. c3!? { Tries to hold together the main pawn chain, but still gives up the tasty h6 snack. }) 21... Qc4 22. Qg4 Nf5 { Black has a strategically winning position. } { [%cal Gf5e3,Gf5h6,Gf5d4,Gf5g7] } 23. Bf2 (23. Qg5?? { Doesn't quite work. } 23... Nxe3 24. Qf6 Rf8 25. Qg7 Nf5 26. Qxh7 Qe2!! { The queen and knight box out all white threats to his own king as well starting to threaten mates themselves. } { [%cal Ge2h5,Gh5h6] }) 23... Nxh6 24. Qg5 Nf5 25. Qf6 O-O { Amazingly, I can finally castle. With no more threats, my opponent could have resigned, but instead he threw one more hail mary. } 26. h4 (26. c3 Qd3 $19 { [%cal Gd3h3] }) 26... Nxd4 { Unnecessary, but clean. } (26... Qe2 { If taking on d4 didn't work, I saw that at least I always had this move to stop h5 in its tracks. }) 27. Bxd4 (27. h5!? Ne2+ 28. Kh2 Nxf4! 29. h6 Nh5 $19 { [%csl Gf6,Gg7] }) 27... Qxd4+ 28. Rf2 Rc3! { Not letting up! } { [%cal Gc3f3,Gd4f2,Gf3h3] } (28... Qe4 29. h5 Qf5 { I was initially considering this safe defense, but then I realized that my opponent's under more threats than me. }) 29. Rf1 (29. h5!? { I made sure every line fails before playing Rc3. } 29... Rf3 { [%cal Gh5h6,Gd4f2,Gf3h3] } 30. h6?? (30. Rf1 Rxf2 { [%cal Gh5h6] } 31. h6 (31. Rxf2 Qd1+ 32. Kg2 Qxh5 $19) (31. c3!? { [%cal Gf2f4] } 31... Rxf1+! 32. Kxf1 Qd1+ 33. Kg2 Qxh5 $19) 31... Rxf4+! { [%cal Gd4g1,Gf4f6] } 32. Kg2 Rxf6) 30... Qxf2+ 31. Kh1 Rh3#) 29... Rxc2 30. h5 Rxf2 31. Rxf2 Qd1+ 32. Kg2 Qxh5 33. Rf3 { [%cal Gh5f5] } 33... Rc8 34. Rf2 h6 { Getting out of perpetuals, and ensuring white can no longer trade queens. I no longer had any aspirations of trading queens because I knew my attack on the white king would win faster than pushing my 4 extra pawns. } 35. Qe7 Rc3! { [%csl Gg7] } 36. Qd8+ (36. Qe8+ Kg7 $19) 36... Kh7 $19 { Forced mate is on the board, so white simply resigned. } { [%cal Gh5h3,Gc3c1,Gc1f1] } 0-1


